 Its reasons are as follows: From my self‑introduction I favor album‑focused, front‑to‑back records with Classic Rock/AOR sensibilities — electric‑guitar drive, inventive sequencing, strong memorable melodies and tight vocal arrangements — and I also enjoy immersive, atmosphere‑first production (layered/ethereal vocal stacks, tasteful reverb and pads, slow‑unfurling melodies and cinematic textures). I explicitly dislike raw, close‑mic acoustic folk and upfront rustic vocal intimacy or records that prioritize rhythmic punch over atmosphere.
Evaluating the two candidates against those points, Hozier (the 2014 self‑titled album) maps closely to my preferences. It’s a cohesive debut that rewards repeated, front‑to‑back listening, built around memorable, hooky songs (e.g., “Take Me to Church”) and a mix of electric and band‑driven arrangements that give the record forward momentum more like rock/AOR than stripped acoustic folk. The production often leans atmospheric: prominent layered vocal arrangements, roomy reverbs and dynamics that reveal details over repeated plays rather than a deliberately “raw” close‑mic intimacy. Those qualities — strong melodies, tight vocal stacks, and a balance of immediacy with cohesive production — are directly in line with what I said I gravitate toward.
By contrast, Elton John’s The Diving Board (2013) is largely piano‑centric, older‑songwriter material with a generally sparse, intimate palette. While it has strong melodies (and merits as a songwriter’s statement), its aesthetic is closer to pared‑down, piano and vocal presentation rather than the electric‑guitar drive and layered, atmospheric mixes I prefer. The Diving Board’s more intimate, sometimes raw organic production and emphasis on piano/songcraft over band‑driven, cinematic textures makes it less congruent with my stated tastes and inclinations. For those reasons I select Hozier and reject The Diving Board.

